item.title: CSP or Reseller, how should I register?
item.dc:creator: Telgorithm
item.description:
Unlike the celebrated dynamics between Jedi vs Sith or Good vs Evil, the differences between a Campaign Service Provider (CSP) and a Reseller isn’t about what is right versus what is wrong. Instead, choosing a path between CSP and Reseller is dependent on your business needs.

The post CSP or Reseller, how should I register? appeared first on Telgorithm.
item.content:encoded:
Foreword

Unlike the celebrated dynamics between Jedi vs Sith or Good vs Evil, the differences between a Campaign Service Provider (CSP) and a Reseller isn’t about what is right versus what is wrong. Instead, choosing a path between CSP and Reseller is dependent on your business needs. For this blog, we will assume that you have some basic understanding of The Campaign Registry (TCR). If you need to brush up on your knowledge of TCR, read: Business Messaging, A2P, and The Campaign Registry.

As a high level recap, to become compliant with A2P 10DLC, we recommend to do the following:

  • Set up your profile as a CSP in TCR;
  • Set up brands and campaigns under your CSP profile;
  • and, Associate phone numbers to each TCR campaign with your Messaging Service Provider (e.g., Telgorithm)
The minimum criteria to become a CSP is to have more than one brand under your CSP profile. If you’re interested in becoming one after reading this blog, schedule a meeting with us to discuss next steps.

What is a Campaign Service Provider (CSP)?

A CSP is the primary user of TCR, working with multiple brands to create and launch messaging campaigns. As a CSP, you own the data behind each brand and each campaign that has been created underneath your CSP profile. Any additional brand vetting that has been paid for is retained under your CSP profile. 

Regarding one-time fees: Under a CSP profile, any one-time fees paid will not need to be paid again when migrating to another messaging provider (e.g., brand registration, additional vetting, etc). 

What is a Reseller?

A Reseller is a secondary user of TCR, meaning that a third-party sits between your company,your brands, and campaigns. For example, if you did not sign up as a CSP, your Messaging Service Provider (third-party) would take care of all brand and campaign registration on your behalf under their CSP profile. This approach may sound enticing but will entrench your business with your messaging provider.

Regarding one-time fees: Under a Reseller profile, any one-time fees paid will need to be paid again when migrating to another CSP, which includes: 1) brand registration fees; 2) mid-month campaign activation fees; 3) T-Mobile activation fees; 4) one-time fees paid for special use cases to the MNOs; and, 5) brand vetting fees. 

Information gathering

To become registered as a CSP or as a Reseller, you will need to gather two types of information from your customers:

  • Gathering brand information. A brand is a legal entity or role responsible for the messaging content in a campaign. A brand can only be submitted for approval by the CSP.
  • Gathering campaign information. A campaign ties together the who (CSP and Brand) and the what (Use Case) for all 10DLC messaging campaigns. A campaign can only be submitted for approval by the CSP.

Gathering brand information

If you’re in the SaaS space, gathering brand information means corralling all of the business data belonging to your customers. All of that information, outlined below, can be populated and then accessed within TCR, using your CSP credentials via an API (or via the TCR portal), a process  Telgorithm can guide you through. As a CSP or a Reseller, you will be gathering the following information to provide to your CSP: 

Mandatory Fields

  • Legal Company Name
  • Country of Registration (or country in which the business resides)
  • Organization Type (e.g., Public, Private, Non-Profit, etc)
  • Tax Number / ID / EIN
  • Business Address
  • Vertical Type (e.g., Agriculture, Media and Communications, Education, etc)
  • Stock Symbol (if Organization Type = Public)
  • Stock Exchange (if Organization Type = Public)
  • First and Last Name (if Organization Type = Sole Proprietor)

Optional Fields

  • DBA or Brand Name
  • EIN Issuing Country
  • DUNS / GIIN / LEI Number
  • Brand’s Website URL

Gathering campaign information

Before creating a campaign, a CSP or a Reseller must do all of the pre-work of gathering information and registering a campaign. As you’re gathering information, we suggest creating a spreadsheet that allows you to capture the following information: 


Important distinction to a CSP: As a Reseller, if you move to another CSP, you forfeit the ownership of this data in TCR, which is 85% of effort towards becoming A2P compliant.

Which one should you choose, and why?

Becoming a CSP is similar to having the “One Ring To Rule Them All”. All brands, campaigns, and brand vetting stays with your CSP profile (you own that data). Another advantage of becoming a CSP is the added flexibility of moving to another messaging provider should your existing one stop meeting your needs (e.g., due to low customer satisfaction, high downtime, low deliverability / throughput, or unfavorable pricing). 

As a a Reseller, everything that your CSP (messaging provider) has built for you in TCR is theirs to keep. In addition,, migrating will require:

  • Rebuilding brands and campaigns in TCR  w/ the new CSP or when you become your own CSP
  • Repaying one-time brand registration and brand vetting fees
  • Reperform brand vetting, where needed

Remember, if you continue to re-register as a Reseller, subsequent provider migrations will also require you to rinse & repeat the steps above. Remember, you do not fully “own” your brands, campaigns, brand vetting, and any additional data that your CSP has entered under your  Reseller profile. 

We enjoy the structural flexibility of being vendor agnostic, so we firmly believe that you should own much of that flexibility as well. Our mission is to earn your business day-after-day. If we stop delivering on value, we’ll even help you move to another provider for free. 

Cost of migrating as a Reseller

The cost of severing your relationship with your CSP is high. To illustrate, we’ve outlined the Cost of Migration below to help you better anticipate costs related to migration as a Reseller:


Bottom line

At the end of the day, we recognize that you must do what is right for your customers and your organization. We know that balancing these finer details isn’t always easy… Feel free to bounce ideas or questions off of us.

Book a meeting with us to discuss whether being a CSP or Reseller is right for you.

item.title: Business Messaging, A2P 10DLC, and The Campaign Registry
item.dc:creator: Telgorithm
item.description:
What does 10 Digit Long Code (10DLC), application-to-person (A2P) and The Campaign Registry (TCR) have in common? We look at basic terms, new updates, and the basics of moving to A2P.

The post Business Messaging, A2P 10DLC, and The Campaign Registry appeared first on Telgorithm.
item.content:encoded:
Terms and definitions to know:

  • Person-to-person (P2P): Defined as text messaging between two people, where no application platform is being used on either side.  
  • Application-to-person (A2P): Defined as text messaging that is sent via an API or an application. 
  • The Campaign Registry (TCR): TCR is the single source registry vendor chosen to specifically validate businesses & their associated messaging campaigns to ensure legitimate use cases (to help MNOs reduce risk of SPAM). 
  • Mobile Network Operator (MNO): Wireless carriers that have access to the end customer or mobile users (e.g.,  ATT, T-Mobile, Verizon, U.S. Cellular, etc).
  • Direct Connect Aggregators (DCA): DCAs are companies that have direct connections to the MNO’s gateways and transmit messages on behalf of its customers such as Telgorithm.
  • Override Services Registry (OSR): NetNumber is the singular registry that provides message signaling on phone numbers. ALL phone numbers must be OSR registered via DCA’s in order to be able to send and receive messages.
  • Campaign Service Provider (CSP): CSP is the provider of messaging services to its customers. A CSP works with its customers, brands, to create and launch new and successful messaging campaigns. Telgorithm is a registered CSP.
  • Brands (Customer): This is the business / entity that is sending messages to end customers mobile phones.
  • Snowshoeing: Snowshoeing involves spreading similar messages across multiple numbers as a way to avoid per number rate limits and volume limitations. Snowshoeing is a common technique used by spammers. Adopting this technique often results in your messages being blocked based on your message content, including your URLs.

What does 10 Digit Long Code (10DLC), application-to-person (A2P) and The Campaign Registry (TCR) have in common? 

These three serve as the magic ingredients for the Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) big self-regulated push to defeat the SMS / MMS Spamosaurus Rex. 

History. 

Before A2P, there was P2P messaging. Started in the 90s, the humble beginnings of P2P messaging started with a “Merry Christmas” command line typed into a computer interface sent to Vodafone’s Richard Jarvis. And like Iron Man’s J.A.R.V.I.S, SMS began to take on a life of its own. People began sending more and more P2P SMS / MMS messages, where finally commercial businesses began to take notice of the most effective communication channel in any sophisticated marketing mix. With stats like 99% SMS / MMS open rate and 95% read within 3 minutes, businesses began to double down on SMS / MMS messaging as an official communication channel for sales and support issues. However, bad actors started to infiltrate, in the form of SPAM, the sacred P2P ecosystem and have diminished the trust between MNOs and mobile users across the United States and Canada. Since A2P and P2P traffic was intermingled, carriers had a hard time protecting end users from unwanted messages.

In the last few years, MNOs have put their proverbial foot down and have launched A2P 10DLC services starting with Verizon, early 2020. With a fully sanctioned path (White Route), businesses around the United States and Canada have an ecosystem that supports higher per message throughput (eliminating any need to circumvent throughput limitations in the P2P ecosystem through snowshoeing) and higher per message deliverability. Think of the A2P 10DLC sanctioned path as air traffic control, allowing good planes to fly freely and removing the bad ones from the sky.

MNOs have partnered with the TCR (for more information read further) and the OSR to deliver the A2P ecosystem and are mandating that all businesses shift to A2P immediately. 

In partnership with TCR, MNOs now have visibility into the messenger and the message which allows the MNOs to provide better qualify service (in the form of higher deliverability and throughput). 

The shift to A2P is a serious one and deserves your immediate attention. Failure to reprioritize your engineering roadmaps could result in service disruptions for you and the brands you represent.

Who’s affected?

If you’re sending a text message via an API (any cloud based service or application) regardless of use case (e.g., an appointment reminder, a two-factor authentication, chatting with a customer over SMS / MMS), you MUST transition your messaging to the A2P ecosystem. MNOs have already started flagging your SMS / MMS as SPAM and are continuing to accelerate the occurrence of blocking your messages from reaching the end consumer, as well as charging higher per message tariffs. Eventually, only true P2P messages will be allowed to traverse the P2P path. 

Still concerned about whether or not you qualify for A2P? Schedule a meeting with us.

How does it all work?

Simply put, the process involves the following: 

  • Within the TCR:

1) registering your company with a CSP (e.g., Telgorithm) or becoming your own CSP; 

2) registering your brands; 

3) registering your 10DLC messaging campaigns; 

  • Messaging service provider (e.g., Telgorithm):

4) associate phone numbers to 10DLC messaging campaigns (you must provide this information to                            your provider); and,

5) update the OSR so that your numbers are    appropriately assigned to your campaigns.

What do I need to do to register? 

You’ll need the following information to register with the TCR:

  • Brand information (this could be thousands if you’re in the SaaS space)
  • Company Name
  • Website URL
  • Tax ID / EIN
  • Point of contact name, contact number, and email address
  • Campaign information (each brand could have more than one campaign; one campaign equals one use case)
  • Campaign registration requires detailed information related to the use case type and sample text messages that will be sent during the campaign. Any deviation related 

Here are some examples of “use cases” for A2P messaging:

Benefits of being on A2P. 

Once you register your campaigns and assign your numbers with the TCR, you’re essentially pre-approved to send messages at the pre-designated throughputs, oftentimes higher than 1 message per second (or 60 messages per minute). Due to the design of the A2P ecosystem, another benefit includes higher deliverability of your text messages (close to 100%; learn how to achieve this by speaking to our representatives). Another benefit of registration with TCR is that the MNOs know who you are and what your content consists of (since you are able to provide sample content), ensuring better deliverability. Admittedly, low deliverability and high throughput means very little to your business goals. 

How much time do I have left? 

It is unclear when MNOs will completely block 100% of A2P-designated traffic traversing the P2P path (known as “Grey Routing”). However, chances are high that you’re experiencing less than 80% deliverability and higher per message carrier fees. 

Remaining thoughts. 

Keeping your messaging services running is a full-time job. Going-to-market with new products or product features is hard enough without a grocery list to check-off at the A2P Supermarket. Allowing Telgorithm to help you bridge the gap between having to learn everything and having the right ally to your messaging stack. 

Schedule a meeting with us if you’d like to chat A2P messaging and all things related.

item.title: How is messaging throughput determined on A2P 10DLC
item.dc:creator: Telgorithm
item.description:
Late July 2021, TCR deployed an Assignment Rule that determines messaging throughput. We break down the assignment process, how throughput volumes are determined, and how to navigate the vetting process.

The post How is messaging throughput determined on A2P 10DLC appeared first on Telgorithm.
item.content:encoded:
Throughput Assignment Overview

Late July 2021, TCR deployed an Assignment Rule that determines messaging throughput. Under the Assignment Rule, there are three categories that your brand can fall into:

  • Category #1: Your brand is verified and is part of the Russell 3000
  • Category #2: Your brand is verified and is not part of the Russell 3000
  • Category #3: Your brand is unverified
    • Unverified brands will need to go through the registration process again or go through a third-party vetting process. 
      • Note #1: If the brand registration information is accurate, then we recommend going through a third-party (e.g., Aegis or WMC Global) to get your unverified brand verified.
    • A brand is tagged as unverified when the legal name and the EIN / Tax ID do not match. As such, it is important to gather complete and accurate information before starting the brand creation process.

The Assignment Rule goes through the following steps to determine your brand’s messaging throughput:

  1. Step #1: The process begins with a verification of the brand’s EIN / Tax ID and legal name. 
  2. Step #2: Once verified, the next step in the process is for The Campaign Registry (TCR) to validate whether your brand is in the Russell 3000. 
  3. Result: 
    1. If your brand is verified and is in the Russell 3000: congratulations, your brand will have the highest throughput possible. 
    2. If your brand is verified and not in the Russell 3000: you will be given a default throughput by the MNO’s (see chart below) If default throughputs do not match your businesses needs, you’ll need to go through additional vetting for higher throughputs. Additional vetting information can be found in the What if I’m not satisfied with my approved throughputs section.

We created a graphical representation below to show how the Assignment Rule works.

Assignment Rule Illustrated

Brand Registration Score (aka Trust Score) will be assigned after a third-party vetting process (not required if initial throughputs are enough for your business needs). The score will then determine your Message Class or Tier, which ultimately determines your brand’s messaging throughput (T-Mobile) or your Campaigns per second/minute throughput (ATT). All of this applies when you’re using a standard campaign type.

Important note: Special campaign types will be granted higher throughputs based on a MNO pre-approval or post-registration process. If you’re unsure how to conduct the registration, we will gladly walk you through that process. Schedule a meeting with us.

Campaign Throughput Schedule

The table below illustrates how each mobile network operator (MNO) regulates throughput based on a Message Class or Tier (this distinction is based on the MNO). As of this writing, Verizon and U.S. Cellular have not drawn this distinction, but we believe both companies will lean closer to AT&T’s mandated messaging throughputs rather than T-Mobile’s.

Note: Based on your Message Class or Tier, your messaging provider should have the MNO specified throughputs built into their messaging platform. If you exceed daily or per minute throughputs, the MNOs could block your message. As such, check with your provider to ensure that the right throughput controls are in place to avoid any potential disruptions.

Don’t know which campaign type to use? Schedule a call with us.

How do MNOs know about my approved throughput? 

The MNOs have binds built directly against TCR. When a campaign is created, the approved throughput is sent electronically to the MNOs directly from TCR. 

Once you’ve completed your Brand and Campaign creation, you’ll need to associate your numbers with the relevant Campaign ID, which is accomplished through your Messaging Aggregator (e.g., Telgorithm, etc). By associating numbers to each Campaign ID, the Messaging Aggregator will update the Override Services Registry (OSR) with this information to help you obtain your approved throughput with each MNO. 

What if I’m not satisfied with my approved throughput?

TCR created a vetting option for those that want to appeal the process for additional review. As a warning, additional vetting does not guarantee a positive outcome. We recommend the following order of operation if you’re going through additional vetting:

  • For non-political campaigns:
  1. Begin your vetting process with Aegis Mobile. This process will be the quickest path to your new Brand Score. Although much more automated and embedded within the TCR, Aegis Mobile may not provide the best outcome for your business needs. WMC Global provides a more thorough approach to vetting, which means that you may receive a better outcome.
  2. If you’re dissatisfied with the results from Aegis Mobile, you can email Aegis Mobile to appeal (although likelihood that the score will change drastically is minimal) OR go through a vetting process with WMC Global, which may yield better results. As of writing this blog, WMC Global is known to take a more holistic approach towards evaluating your business.
  • For political campaigns: 
  1. You will need to begin your vetting process with Campaign Verify. 

TCR has partnered with the following:

  • Aegis Mobile – Aegis mobile is one of the vetting partners approved by the registry. Through its partnership, The Campaign Registry has created a more automated submission process within its portal to submit the additional vetting request. The cost of this request is a one-time non-refundable fee of $40.00. The request process is usually completed within minutes. However, it can take up to a week.

Note: Once you receive your new Brand Score with Aegis, you won’t need to take additional steps (with TCR or your Messaging Aggregator). 

  • WMC Global – WMC Global is another approved vetting partner of The Campaign Registry. If you wish to go through them for added vetting, it would need to be done directly. Can do so by clicking here. If approval is given, they will give you a unique ‘vetting Identifier’. Telgorithm can then import that identifier into your Brand’s profile within the registry which will instantly give you the higher approved throughputs. For the associated costs, you will need to reach out to WMC GLOBAL directly. The initial WMC Global registration process can take approximately one week to complete. Once complete, vetting is instant!

Note: Once you receive your new Brand Score, you will need to import the results via the “Import Vetting” under each Brand page. Upon adding the Vetting ID, your Brand Score will update immediately.

  • Campaign Verify – Campaign Verify is another Campaign Registry approved vetting partner. Campaign Verify is a non-partisan, non-profit service for US political campaigns, parties, and PACs to verify their identity. If your business is running political campaigns, you must go through Campaign Verify for additional vetting. If approval is given, they will give you a unique ‘vetting Identifier’. You can then import that identifier into your Brand’s profile within the registry which will instantly give you the higher approved throughputs. For the associated costs, you will need to reach out to Campaign Verify directly.

Note: Once you receive your new Brand Score, you will need to import the results via the “Import Vetting” under each Brand page. Upon adding the Vetting ID, your Brand Score will update immediately.

Still have questions regarding the vetting process? Schedule a meeting with us.
